{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506165"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2528"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2528"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.72,0.03,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2528"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26546"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"668"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman presents with a two month history of generalised, progressive weakness. Her medical history is significant only for hypertension. Her medication list includes a calcium channel blocker. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min and blood pressure 135/75mmHg. Other vital parameters are within normal limits. Neurological examination demonstrates symmetrical weakness of 4/5 in all four limbs. Her reflexes, coordination and sensation all appear normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer serum biochemistry reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa 140 mmol/L (137-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK 2.5 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl 113 mmol/L (100-109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 15 mmol/L (22-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnion Gap 20 mmol/L (18-22)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.20 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe urine chemistry shows the presence of glucose, amino acids, and phosphate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lactic acidosis","Glomerulonephritis","Renal tubular acidosis","Tumour lysis syndrome","Light chain nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question examines the different causes of metabolic acidosis (low pH accompanied by a low bicarbonate). A useful concept to be familiar with is that of the anion gap, which helps to categorise the possible causes into either high anion gap (HAGMA) or normal anion gap (NAGMA) metabolic acidosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe two most common causes of NAGMA as GI loss in the forms of diarrhoea, followed by\u003Cstrong\u003E renal tubular acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E. In these cases, the mechanism of acidosis is a loss of bicarbonate, which the body compensates for in the form of chloride (hence the alternative name of hyperchloremic acidosis). In these cases, the loss of negative bicarbonate is compensated for by gain of chloride, which are both measured in the calculation of an anion gap and hence the \u0022normal\u0022 anion gap is preserved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy contrast, in HAGMA the low bicarbonate is replaced by \u0022unmeasured\u0022 anions, usually lactate or ketones (the most common cause of HAGMA is either ketoacidosis or \u003Cstrong\u003Elactic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E). As a result, in these cases the anion gap is elevated due to the presence of these unmeasured anions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has severe hypokalaemia and a NAGMA. The additional findings of abnormal loss of phosphate, glucose and amino acids should prompt you to consider a renal cause, namely renal tubular acidosis, of which there are 4 different subtypes characterized by varying electrolyte abnormalities depending on whether the defect is proximal or distal in the tubules. The exact subtype in this case is type 2 renal tubular acidosis, where the defect is in proximal electrolyte resorption, resulting in urinary bicarbonate loss. Hypokalaemia is a feature of type 1 and 2 renal tubular acidosis, whilst type 4 is distinguished as it has high potassium (type 3 is exceedingly rare!!!). The low potassium in this case is the likely cause of her limb weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of causes of type 2 RTA including Fanconi syndrome (a rare inherited or acquired disease), which given the additional urinary loss of phosphate, glucose and amino acids, is the likely cause of her presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs discussed above, lactic acidosis is a cause of HAGMA and is thus an unlikely cause of the above presentation, while \u003Cstrong\u003Eglomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is also unlikely as there was no blood or protein on urinalysis. \u003Cstrong\u003ETumour lysis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E would have high potassium on electrolyte panels and unlikely to have the same biochemical abnormalities. \u003Cstrong\u003ELight chain nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare disorder and more common presents as an acute kidney injury or chronic kidney disease, rather than the current clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The two most common causes of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis are GI loss in the forms of diarrhoea, followed by renal tubular acidosis."],"references":["Mustaqeem R, Arif A. Renal tubular acidosis. In: Statpearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519044/","Keefe P, Bokhari SYA. Fanconi syndrome. In: Statpearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534872/#:~:text=Fanconi%20syndrome%20requires%20that%20distal,or%20problems%20with%20transport%20carriers.","Sanders PW. Mechanisms of light chain injury along the tubular nephron. JASN. 2012; 23(11): 1777-781. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22997259/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2528"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26546"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-20T12:38:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-20T12:38:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2528"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41628"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group